#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:-1
msgid ""
"Learn the fundamental Spack commands for managing software packages, "
"including how to find, inspect, install, and remove them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:13
msgid "Package Fundamentals"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:15
msgid ""
"Spack provides a comprehensive ecosystem of software packages that you can "
"install. In this section you'll learn:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:18
msgid "How to discover which packages are available,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:19
msgid "How to get detailed information about specific packages,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:20
msgid "How to install/uninstall packages, and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:21
msgid "How to discover, and use, software that has been installed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:28
msgid "Listing Available Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:30
msgid ""
"To install software with Spack, you need to know what software is available. "
"You can search for available packages on the `packages.spack.io <https://"
"packages.spack.io>`_ website or by using the ``spack list`` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:36
msgid "``spack list``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:38
msgid ""
"The ``spack list`` command prints out a list of all of the packages Spack "
"can install:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:40
msgid "$ spack list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:44
msgid ""
"Packages are listed by name in alphabetical order. A pattern can be used to "
"narrow the list, and the following rules apply:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:47
msgid ""
"A pattern with no wildcards (``*`` or ``?``) is treated as if it starts and "
"ends with ``*``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:48
msgid "All patterns are case-insensitive"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:50
msgid ""
"To search for all packages whose names contain the word ``sql`` you can run "
"the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:52
msgid "$ spack list sql"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:56
msgid ""
"A few options are also provided for more specific searches. For instance, it "
"is possible to search the description of packages for a match. A way to list "
"all the packages whose names or descriptions contain the word ``quantum`` is "
"the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:60
msgid "$ spack list -d quantum"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:68
msgid "``spack info``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:70
msgid ""
"To get more information about a particular package from `spack list`, use "
"`spack info`. Just supply the name of a package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:76
msgid ""
"Most of the information is self-explanatory. The *safe versions* are "
"versions for which Spack knows the checksum. Spack uses this checksum to "
"verify that the versions are downloaded without errors or malicious changes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:80
msgid ""
":ref:`Dependencies <sec-specs>` and :ref:`virtual dependencies <sec-virtual-"
"dependencies>` are described in more detail later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:85
msgid "``spack versions``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:87
msgid ""
"To see *more* available versions of a package, run ``spack versions``. For "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:93
msgid ""
"There are two sections in the output. *Safe versions* are versions for which "
"Spack has a checksum on file. It can verify that these versions are "
"downloaded correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:97
msgid ""
"In many cases, Spack can also show you what versions are available out on "
"the web -- these are *remote versions*. Spack gets this information by "
"scraping it directly from package web pages. Depending on the package and "
"how its releases are organized, Spack may or may not be able to find remote "
"versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:104
msgid "``spack providers``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:106
msgid ""
"You can see what packages provide a particular virtual package using ``spack "
"providers``. If you wanted to see what packages provide ``mpi``, you would "
"just run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:112
msgid ""
"And if you *only* wanted to see packages that provide MPI-2, you would add a "
"version specifier to the spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:117
msgid ""
"Notice that the package versions that provide insufficient MPI versions are "
"now filtered out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:120
msgid "Installing and Uninstalling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:125
msgid "``spack install``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:127
msgid ""
"``spack install`` will install any package shown by ``spack list``. For "
"example, to install the latest version of the ``mpileaks`` package, you "
"might type this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:130
msgid "$ spack install mpileaks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:134
msgid ""
"If ``mpileaks`` depends on other packages, Spack will install the "
"dependencies first. It then fetches the ``mpileaks`` tarball, expands it, "
"verifies that it was downloaded without errors, builds it, and installs it "
"in its own directory under ``$SPACK_ROOT/opt``. You'll see a number of "
"messages from Spack, a lot of build output, and a message that the package "
"is installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:138
msgid ""
"$ spack install mpileaks\n"
"... dependency build output ...\n"
"==> Installing mpileaks-1.0-ph7pbnhl334wuhogmugriohcwempqry2\n"
"==> No binary for mpileaks-1.0-ph7pbnhl334wuhogmugriohcwempqry2 found: "
"installing from source\n"
"==> mpileaks: Executing phase: 'autoreconf'\n"
"==> mpileaks: Executing phase: 'configure'\n"
"==> mpileaks: Executing phase: 'build'\n"
"==> mpileaks: Executing phase: 'install'\n"
"[+] ~/spack/opt/linux-rhel7-broadwell/gcc-8.1.0/mpileaks-1.0-"
"ph7pbnhl334wuhogmugriohcwempqry2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:150
msgid ""
"The last line, with the ``[+]``, indicates where the package is installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:152
msgid ""
"Add the Spack debug option (one or more times) -- ``spack -d install "
"mpileaks`` -- to get additional (and even more verbose) output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:155
msgid "Building a specific version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:157
msgid ""
"Spack can also build *specific versions* of a package. To do this, just add "
"``@`` after the package name, followed by a version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:160
msgid "$ spack install mpich@3.0.4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:164
msgid ""
"Any number of versions of the same package can be installed at once without "
"interfering with each other. This is useful for multi-user sites, as "
"installing a version that one user needs will not disrupt existing "
"installations for other users."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:167
msgid ""
"In addition to different versions, Spack can customize the compiler, compile-"
"time options (variants), compiler flags, and target architecture of an "
"installation. Spack is unique in that it can also configure the "
"*dependencies* a package is built with. For example, two configurations of "
"the same version of a package, one built with boost 1.39.0, and the other "
"version built with version 1.43.0, can coexist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:171
msgid ""
"This can all be done on the command line using the *spec* syntax. Spack "
"calls the descriptor used to refer to a particular package configuration a "
"**spec**. In the commands above, ``mpileaks`` and ``mpileaks@3.0.4`` are "
"both valid *specs*. We'll talk more about how you can use them to customize "
"an installation in :ref:`sec-specs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:177
msgid "Reusing installed dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:179
msgid ""
"By default, when you run ``spack install``, Spack tries hard to reuse "
"existing installations as dependencies, either from a local store or from "
"remote buildcaches, if configured. This minimizes unwanted rebuilds of "
"common dependencies, in particular if you update Spack frequently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:182
msgid ""
"In case you want the latest versions and configurations to be installed "
"instead, you can add the ``--fresh`` option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:184
msgid "$ spack install --fresh mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:188
msgid ""
"Reusing installations in this mode is \"accidental\" and happens only if "
"there's a match between existing installations and what Spack would have "
"installed anyway."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:190
msgid ""
"You can use the ``spack spec -I mpich`` command to see what will be reused "
"and what will be built before you install."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:192
msgid ""
"You can configure Spack to use the ``--fresh`` behavior by default in "
"``concretizer.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:194
msgid ""
"concretizer:\n"
"  reuse: false"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:202
msgid "``spack uninstall``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:204
msgid ""
"To uninstall a package, run ``spack uninstall <package>``. This will ask the "
"user for confirmation before completely removing the directory in which the "
"package was installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:207 ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:223
msgid "$ spack uninstall mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:211
msgid ""
"If there are still installed packages that depend on the package to be "
"uninstalled, Spack will refuse to uninstall it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:213
msgid ""
"To uninstall a package and every package that depends on it, you may give "
"the ``--dependents`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:215
msgid "$ spack uninstall --dependents mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:219
msgid ""
"will display a list of all the packages that depend on ``mpich`` and, upon "
"confirmation, will uninstall them in the correct order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:221
msgid "A command like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:227
msgid ""
"may be ambiguous if multiple ``mpich`` configurations are installed. For "
"example, if both ``mpich@3.0.2`` and ``mpich@3.1`` are installed, ``mpich`` "
"could refer to either one. Because it cannot determine which one to "
"uninstall, Spack will ask you either to provide a version number to remove "
"the ambiguity or use the ``--all`` option to uninstall all matching packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:231
msgid "You may force uninstall a package with the ``--force`` option"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:233
msgid "$ spack uninstall --force mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:237
msgid ""
"but you risk breaking other installed packages. In general, it is safer to "
"remove dependent packages *before* removing their dependencies or to use the "
"``--dependents`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:244
msgid "Garbage collection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:246
msgid ""
"When Spack builds software from sources, it often installs tools that are "
"needed only to build or test other software. These are not necessary at "
"runtime. To support cases where removing these tools can be a benefit, Spack "
"provides the ``spack gc`` (\"garbage collector\") command, which will "
"uninstall all unneeded packages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:250
msgid ""
"$ spack find\n"
"==> 24 installed packages\n"
"-- linux-ubuntu18.04-broadwell / gcc@9.0.1 ----------------------\n"
"autoconf@2.69    findutils@4.6.0  libiconv@1.16        libszip@2.1.1  "
"m4@1.4.18    openjpeg@2.3.1  pkgconf@1.6.3  util-macros@1.19.1\n"
"automake@1.16.1  gdbm@1.18.1      libpciaccess@0.13.5  libtool@2.4.6  "
"mpich@3.3.2  openssl@1.1.1d  readline@8.0   xz@5.2.4\n"
"cmake@3.16.1     hdf5@1.10.5      libsigsegv@2.12      libxml2@2.9.9  "
"ncurses@6.1  perl@5.30.0     texinfo@6.5    zlib@1.2.11\n"
"\n"
"$ spack gc\n"
"==> The following packages will be uninstalled:\n"
"\n"
"    -- linux-ubuntu18.04-broadwell / gcc@9.0.1 ----------------------\n"
"    vn47edz autoconf@2.69    6m3f2qn findutils@4.6.0  ubl6bgk libtool@2.4.6  "
"pksawhz openssl@1.1.1d  urdw22a readline@8.0\n"
"    ki6nfw5 automake@1.16.1  fklde6b gdbm@1.18.1      b6pswuo m4@1.4.18      "
"k3s2csy perl@5.30.0     lp5ya3t texinfo@6.5\n"
"    ylvgsov cmake@3.16.1     5omotir libsigsegv@2.12  leuzbbh ncurses@6.1    "
"5vmfbrq pkgconf@1.6.3   5bmv4tg util-macros@1.19.1\n"
"\n"
"==> Do you want to proceed? [y/N] y\n"
"\n"
"[ ... ]\n"
"\n"
"$ spack find\n"
"==> 9 installed packages\n"
"-- linux-ubuntu18.04-broadwell / gcc@9.0.1 ----------------------\n"
"hdf5@1.10.5  libiconv@1.16  libpciaccess@0.13.5  libszip@2.1.1  "
"libxml2@2.9.9  mpich@3.3.2  openjpeg@2.3.1  xz@5.2.4  zlib@1.2.11"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:276
msgid ""
"In the example above, ``spack gc`` scans the package database. It keeps only "
"the packages that were explicitly installed by a user, along with their "
"required ``link`` and ``run`` dependencies (including transitive "
"dependencies). All other packages, such as build-only dependencies or "
"orphaned packages, are identified as \"garbage\" and removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:280
msgid ""
"You can check :ref:`cmd-spack-find-metadata` to see how to query for "
"explicitly installed packages or :ref:`dependency-types` for a more thorough "
"treatment of dependency types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:285
msgid "Marking packages explicit or implicit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:287
msgid ""
"By default, Spack will mark packages a user installs as explicitly "
"installed, while all of its dependencies will be marked as implicitly "
"installed. Packages can be marked manually as explicitly or implicitly "
"installed by using ``spack mark``. This can be used in combination with "
"``spack gc`` to clean up packages that are no longer required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:291
msgid ""
"$ spack install m4\n"
"==> 29005: Installing libsigsegv\n"
"[...]\n"
"==> 29005: Installing m4\n"
"[...]\n"
"\n"
"$ spack install m4 ^libsigsegv@2.11\n"
"==> 39798: Installing libsigsegv\n"
"[...]\n"
"==> 39798: Installing m4\n"
"[...]\n"
"\n"
"$ spack find -d\n"
"==> 4 installed packages\n"
"-- linux-fedora32-haswell / gcc@10.1.1 --------------------------\n"
"libsigsegv@2.11\n"
"\n"
"libsigsegv@2.12\n"
"\n"
"m4@1.4.18\n"
"    libsigsegv@2.12\n"
"\n"
"m4@1.4.18\n"
"    libsigsegv@2.11\n"
"\n"
"$ spack gc\n"
"==> There are no unused specs. Spack's store is clean.\n"
"\n"
"$ spack mark -i m4 ^libsigsegv@2.11\n"
"==> m4@1.4.18 : marking the package implicit\n"
"\n"
"$ spack gc\n"
"==> The following packages will be uninstalled:\n"
"\n"
"    -- linux-fedora32-haswell / gcc@10.1.1 --------------------------\n"
"    5fj7p2o libsigsegv@2.11  c6ensc6 m4@1.4.18\n"
"\n"
"==> Do you want to proceed? [y/N]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:332
msgid ""
"In the example above, we ended up with two versions of ``m4`` because they "
"depend on different versions of ``libsigsegv``. ``spack gc`` will not remove "
"any of the packages because both versions of ``m4`` have been installed "
"explicitly and both versions of ``libsigsegv`` are required by the ``m4`` "
"packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:335
msgid ""
"``spack mark`` can also be used to implement upgrade workflows. The "
"following example demonstrates how ``spack mark`` and ``spack gc`` can be "
"used to only keep the current version of a package installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:338
msgid ""
"When updating Spack via ``git pull``, new versions for either ``libsigsegv`` "
"or ``m4`` might be introduced. This will cause Spack to install duplicates. "
"Because we only want to keep one version, we mark everything as implicitly "
"installed before updating Spack. If there is no new version for either of "
"the packages, ``spack install`` will simply mark them as explicitly "
"installed, and ``spack gc`` will not remove them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:343
msgid ""
"$ spack install m4\n"
"==> 62843: Installing libsigsegv\n"
"[...]\n"
"==> 62843: Installing m4\n"
"[...]\n"
"\n"
"$ spack mark -i -a\n"
"==> m4@1.4.18 : marking the package implicit\n"
"\n"
"$ git pull\n"
"[...]\n"
"\n"
"$ spack install m4\n"
"[...]\n"
"==> m4@1.4.18 : marking the package explicit\n"
"[...]\n"
"\n"
"$ spack gc\n"
"==> There are no unused specs. Spack's store is clean."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:365
msgid ""
"When using this workflow for installations that contain more packages, care "
"must be taken to either only mark selected packages or issue ``spack "
"install`` for all packages that should be kept."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:367
msgid ""
"You can check :ref:`cmd-spack-find-metadata` to see how to query for "
"explicitly or implicitly installed packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:372
msgid "Non-Downloadable Tarballs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:374
msgid ""
"The tarballs for some packages cannot be automatically downloaded by Spack. "
"This could be for a number of reasons:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:377
msgid ""
"The author requires users to manually accept a license agreement before "
"downloading (e.g., ``jdk`` and ``galahad``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:379
msgid ""
"The software is proprietary and cannot be downloaded on the open Internet."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:381
msgid ""
"To install these packages, one must create a mirror and manually add the "
"tarballs in question to it (see :ref:`mirrors`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:383
msgid ""
"Create a directory for the mirror. You can create this directory anywhere "
"you like, it does not have to be inside ``~/.spack``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:386
msgid "$ mkdir ~/.spack/manual_mirror"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:390
msgid "Register the mirror with Spack by creating ``~/.spack/mirrors.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:392
msgid ""
"mirrors:\n"
"  manual: file://~/.spack/manual_mirror"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:397
msgid ""
"Put your tarballs in it. Tarballs should be named ``<package>/<package>-"
"<version>.tar.gz``. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:401
msgid ""
"$ ls -l manual_mirror/galahad\n"
"\n"
"-rw-------. 1 me me 11657206 Jun 21 19:25 galahad-2.60003.tar.gz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:407
msgid "Install as usual:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:409
msgid "$ spack install galahad"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:415
msgid "Seeing Installed Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:417
msgid ""
"We know that ``spack list`` shows you the names of available packages, but "
"how do you figure out which are already installed?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:422
msgid "``spack find``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:424
msgid ""
"``spack find`` shows the *specs* of installed packages. A spec is like a "
"name, but it has a version, compiler, architecture, and build options "
"associated with it. In Spack, you can have many installations of the same "
"package with different specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../package_fundamentals.rst:428
msgid "Running ``spack find`` with no arguments lists installed packages:"
msgstr ""

